explanation:
To decide whether any operation in OS_QueueDelete is dead code you must know the side-effects and semantic obligations of each call and the meanings of relevant types/constants: 

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Determines whether the initial call only computes a return code or also establishes state (e.g. a transaction or lock) that must be cleaned up; if it has side-effects then calls depending on its success may not be removable.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: Part of GetById’s implementation; needed to see whether a transaction/lock is created (i.e. side-effect that requires later finalization).
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: Helps determine whether GetById maps the id to internal structures and whether that mapping produces required state/notifications.
- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: Shows how the token is formed/modified by GetById (affects whether subsequent operations use or must undo token state).
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Used on error paths inside GetById; required to understand cleanup semantics and whether FinalizeDelete is mandatory.
- OS_QueueDelete_Impl: The core delete implementation — needed to know whether it has observable side-effects (resource deallocation, notifications) such that removing its call would change behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Used by the delete implementation; needed to understand how the token maps to concrete object state and side-effects of delete_impl.
- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete: Called after delete_impl; must inspect whether it performs essential cleanup/notification (not just returning the same code), so its removal could change behavior.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish: Called by FinalizeDelete; shows whether transaction/lock is finished and whether notifications or other global state changes occur.
- OS_NotifyEvent: If FinalizeDelete triggers notifications, these are observable side-effects — removing them could change program behaviour.
- osal_id_t: The ID type is necessary to know value ranges and whether some ids are special (affecting reachability vs. deadness).
- OS_object_token_t: The token structure layout/fields are required to know what state GetById/ConvertToken/FinalizeDelete/QueueDelete_Impl manipulate and whether those manipulations are observable.
- OS_SUCCESS: The success constant is needed to reason about control flow and which branches execute.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE and LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: The lock mode and object-type constants passed to GetById indicate acquisition semantics and object-class dependent behavior (affecting whether cleanup is required).

In short: verifying the absence of dead code requires knowing whether any of these calls or token manipulations have externally observable side-effects (allocations, locks, notifications, global state changes). The listed symbols provide the necessary definitions and implementation-level behaviors to make that determination.
